**DS-MLOps Part 4: ML Landscape**

**Python 3.12+ | Author: Anthony Faustine**

## Before you begin

This notebook is the code companion to Chapters 1-3. Those chapters built the mental model: what ML is, how to frame a problem, and how to diagnose a model. This notebook implements every one of those ideas in code using the scikit-learn API.

Throughout, you will work with a real hotel booking dataset. Two predictions have direct revenue impact: **how much will a booking earn?** (regression) and **will this booking cancel before arrival?** (classification). By the end you will have trained, evaluated, and saved correct models for both.

> Callout markers used throughout this notebook are explained on the [book cover page](../../index.qmd#callout-guide).

::: {.callout-note collapse="true" icon=false}
## Topics covered

| Topic | Why it matters |
|---|---|
| **sklearn API contract** | Every sklearn class follows the same fit/transform/predict pattern |
| **Feature scaling** | Most algorithms require features on a comparable scale |
| **Train/test splitting** | Test data must never influence training |
| **Baseline models** | Any model that cannot beat a dummy is not learning |
| **Evaluation metrics** | MAE, RMSE, R2 for regression; precision, recall, F1 for classification |
| **Cross-validation** | A single split gives one noisy score; CV gives a distribution |
| **Learning curves** | Diagnose underfitting, overfitting, and data limitations |
| **Model persistence** | Save a trained model so inference does not require retraining |
:::

::: {.callout-note collapse="true" icon=false}
## Learning Objectives

By the end of Part 25 you will be able to:

| # | Skill | Covered in |
|---|---|---|
| 1 | Describe the sklearn API contract and apply it to any estimator | Sec. 1 |
| 2 | Load a real dataset and identify numerical features and targets | Sec. 2 |
| 3 | Apply StandardScaler and MinMaxScaler, fitting only on training data | Sec. 3 |
| 4 | Split data with train_test_split, using stratification for classification | Sec. 4 |
| 5 | Establish a DummyRegressor/DummyClassifier baseline before any model | Sec. 5 |
| 6 | Train and evaluate LinearRegression and LogisticRegression | Sec. 6 |
| 7 | Use cross_val_score with KFold and StratifiedKFold | Sec. 7 |
| 8 | Compute and interpret a learning curve | Sec. 8 |
| 9 | Save and reload a trained model with joblib | Sec. 9 |
| 10 | Build a type-annotated end-to-end training function | Capstone |
:::

