## 2. The Dataset: Hotel Booking Demand

This notebook uses six features that are known **at the time of booking** (no information that only becomes available after the guest arrives):

| Feature | Type | Meaning |
|---|---|---|
| `lead_time` | int | Days between booking date and arrival date |
| `stays_in_weekend_nights` | int | Number of Saturday/Sunday nights reserved |
| `stays_in_week_nights` | int | Number of Monday-Friday nights reserved |
| `adults` | int | Number of adult guests |
| `previous_cancellations` | int | Number of times this customer cancelled a prior booking |
| `booking_changes` | int | Number of times the booking was modified |

Two prediction targets:

| Target | Task | Business question |
|---|---|---|
| `adr` | Regression | What average daily rate (euros/night) will this booking generate? |
| `is_canceled` | Classification | Will this booking cancel before arrival? |

Categorical features (`hotel`, `meal`, `market_segment`, `distribution_channel`, `customer_type`, `deposit_type`) are available in the raw dataset but require one-hot encoding. They are intentionally reserved for the **Pipeline notebook** (Part 26), where `ColumnTransformer` handles them correctly.

::: {#73b4bb59 .cell execution_count=4}
``` {.python .cell-code}
TARGET_REG: str = "adr"
TARGET_CLF: str = "is_canceled"

