## 3. Preprocessing: Feature Scaling

Look at the feature ranges below (from `describe()`):

| Feature | Typical range |
|---|---|
| `lead_time` | 0 to 629 |
| `stays_in_week_nights` | 0 to 19 |
| `adults` | 0 to 4 (mostly) |
| `previous_cancellations` | 0 to 26 |

If you feed these raw values into a gradient-descent optimiser (as used inside `LogisticRegression`), the loss surface is elongated along the `lead_time` axis and nearly flat along the `adults` axis. The optimiser moves slowly and may not converge within the default iteration limit.

**StandardScaler** fixes this by transforming each feature to zero mean and unit variance:

$$z = \frac{x - \mu}{\sigma}$$

After scaling, all features live on the same numerical scale, and the optimiser can take equally-sized steps in every direction.

::: {#a159716d .cell execution_count=9}
``` {.python .cell-code}
# Show the scale problem before doing anything
print("Feature ranges BEFORE scaling:")
print(f"  {'Feature':<28} {'min':>8} {'max':>8} {'std':>8}")
print("  " + "-" * 56)
for i, feat in enumerate(FEATURES):
    print(f"  {feat:<28} {X[:, i].min():>8.1f} {X[:, i].max():>8.1f} "
          f"{X[:, i].std():>8.2f}")

# StandardScaler: fit on X to demonstrate (we will fit on X_train only in Sec. 4)
scaler_ss = StandardScaler()
X_ss = scaler_ss.fit_transform(X)

print("\nFeature statistics AFTER StandardScaler:")
print(f"  {'Feature':<28} {'mean':>8} {'std':>8}")
print("  " + "-" * 46)
for i, feat in enumerate(FEATURES):
    print(f"  {feat:<28} {X_ss[:, i].mean():>8.4f} {X_ss[:, i].std():>8.4f}")
print("\nAll features now have mean ~ 0 and std ~ 1.")
```

