## 4. Splitting the Data

The test set is the final judge of generalisation. It simulates bookings the model has never seen. If any information from the test rows influences the model during training -- through scaling, encoding, or feature selection -- the test score is no longer an honest estimate of real-world performance.

The standard split:
- **Training set (80%)**: the model sees these rows during `fit()`.
- **Test set (20%)**: held completely aside; used only for final evaluation.

After splitting, we fit the scaler on training data only, then transform both splits.

::: {#82601edd .cell execution_count=12}
``` {.python .cell-code}
# Regression split
X_train, X_test, y_train, y_test = train_test_split(
    X, y_reg, test_size=0.20, random_state=42
)

# Fit the scaler on TRAINING data, then transform both splits
scaler = StandardScaler()
X_train_s = scaler.fit_transform(X_train)  # fit + transform
X_test_s  = scaler.transform(X_test)       # transform only (no fit)

logger.info(f"Regression -- Train: {X_train.shape[0]:,} rows, "
            f"Test: {X_test.shape[0]:,} rows")
logger.info(f"Train ADR mean: {y_train.mean():.2f}  Test ADR mean: {y_test.mean():.2f}")
logger.info("Similar means confirm the split is representative.")
```
