:::


**Reading the residual plot below:** ideally, residuals scatter randomly around the zero line across all predicted values. A systematic pattern reveals that the model is missing something:

- A **fan shape** (wider spread at higher values) means the model's error grows with the prediction -- common with price data. A log-transform of `adr` often helps.
- A **curve** means the relationship is non-linear and a linear model cannot capture it.

::: {#334ea5c9 .cell execution_count=19}
``` {.python .cell-code}
y_pred_lin = lin_reg.predict(X_test_s)
resid_df = pd.DataFrame({
    "predicted": y_pred_lin,
    "residual": y_test - y_pred_lin,
})

(
    ggplot(resid_df, aes(x="predicted", y="residual"))
    + geom_point(alpha=0.15, size=0.8, color=INFO)
    + geom_hline(yintercept=0, color=DANGER, linetype="dashed", size=1)
    + labs(
        title="Residual Plot: LinearRegression on ADR",
        subtitle="Fan shape at higher values suggests heteroscedasticity",
        x="Predicted ADR (euros/night)",
        y="Residual  (actual - predicted)",
    )
    + modern_theme(grid=True)
)
```

