## 7. Cross-Validation

The test-set score from Section 6 is a single number from one particular random split. Depending on which 20% of rows ended up in the test set, that number could be a few percentage points higher or lower than the true generalisation performance.

Cross-validation solves this by rotating which rows are held out. With 5-fold CV:

1. The training data is divided into 5 equal parts ("folds").
2. In round 1, fold 1 is held out as validation; the model trains on folds 2-5.
3. In round 2, fold 2 is held out; the model trains on 1, 3, 4, 5.
4. ... and so on for all 5 rounds.

The result is 5 scores, one per fold. Their mean and standard deviation give a much more reliable estimate of performance than any single split.

::: {#b5b6d8c8 .cell execution_count=22}
``` {.python .cell-code}
# 5-fold CV on the TRAINING set (never touch the test set during model selection)
cv_scores_reg = cross_val_score(
    LinearRegression(),
    X_train_s,
    y_train,
    cv=KFold(n_splits=5, shuffle=True, random_state=42),
    scoring="r2",
    n_jobs=-1,
)

logger.info("LinearRegression 5-fold CV (R2):")
logger.info(f"  Per fold: {cv_scores_reg.round(4)}")
logger.info(f"  Mean:     {cv_scores_reg.mean():.4f}")
logger.info(f"  Std:      {cv_scores_reg.std():.4f}")
logger.info(
    f"  Single test-set R2 was {lin_metrics['r2']:.4f} -- "
    "CV gives a distribution of {:.4f} +/- {:.4f}".format(
        cv_scores_reg.mean(), cv_scores_reg.std()
    )
)
```
