<div style='background:#EAF3FA;border-left:5px solid #0369A1;padding:14px 18px;border-radius:6px;margin:16px 0'><span style='font-weight:600;color:#0369A1'><i class="bi bi-info-circle-fill"></i> Key Concept: Cross-validation gives a distribution, not a point estimate</span><br><br>A single test score has high variance. Two models that produce 0.62 and 0.65 on one split might swap rankings on a different split. Cross-validation reduces this variance by averaging over multiple splits. The standard deviation across folds tells you how stable the model is: a low std means the score is consistent regardless of which data the model trains on, which is a sign of a well-generalising model.</div>

## 8. Learning Curves

A learning curve plots model performance against **the amount of training data used**. It answers two diagnostic questions:

1. **Has the model plateaued?** If validation score stops improving as you add more data, the bottleneck is the model's representational capacity, not the data volume. Adding more data will not help.
2. **Is there a training/validation gap?** A large gap between training score and validation score means the model is overfitting: it memorises training rows but fails to generalise.

**Four patterns to recognise:**

| Pattern | Training score | Validation score | Diagnosis |
|---|---|---|---|
| Underfitting | Low | Low (similar) | Model too simple; try more features or a more expressive model |
| Overfitting | High | Much lower | Model too complex; try regularisation or more data |
| Data-limited | Moderate | Converging slowly | More data would help |
| Good fit | High | High (small gap) | Model is well-calibrated |

::: {#d63ee320 .cell execution_count=24}
``` {.python .cell-code}
train_sizes, train_scores, val_scores = learning_curve(
    LinearRegression(),
    X_train_s,
    y_train,
    train_sizes=np.linspace(0.05, 1.0, 15),
    cv=KFold(n_splits=5, shuffle=True, random_state=42),
    scoring="r2",
    n_jobs=-1,
)

train_mean = train_scores.mean(axis=1)
val_mean   = val_scores.mean(axis=1)

logger.info(f"Train R2 at full data:      {train_mean[-1]:.4f}")
logger.info(f"Validation R2 at full data: {val_mean[-1]:.4f}")
logger.info(f"Gap (overfit signal):       {train_mean[-1] - val_mean[-1]:.4f}")
```
