## 9. Model Persistence

Training is expensive. A model trained on 93,000 rows of hotel data takes CPU time and RAM. For production, you train once and save the result to disk. At inference time, you load the saved model and call `predict()` directly -- no retraining.

`joblib` serialises Python objects to disk efficiently. For sklearn models, it is faster than `pickle` on objects containing large NumPy arrays (which most fitted estimators do).

**Critical:** save the scaler alongside the model. A model trained on standardised data requires standardised input at inference. If you save only the model and lose the scaler, the saved artefact is unusable.

::: {#7b5bc7b3 .cell execution_count=27}
``` {.python .cell-code}
MODEL_DIR = Path("models")
MODEL_DIR.mkdir(exist_ok=True)
MODEL_PATH = MODEL_DIR / "linreg_adr.joblib"

# Bundle: save scaler + model + feature list together
# The feature list ensures the bundle is self-documenting: you always know
# which columns to pass in which order when calling predict().
bundle = {
    "scaler":   scaler,
    "model":    lin_reg,
    "features": FEATURES,
    "target":   TARGET_REG,
}
joblib.dump(bundle, MODEL_PATH)
logger.info(f"Bundle saved: {MODEL_PATH} ({MODEL_PATH.stat().st_size / 1024:.1f} KB)")

# Reload and verify: predictions must be identical to the originals
loaded = joblib.load(MODEL_PATH)
y_check = loaded["model"].predict(loaded["scaler"].transform(X_test))

assert np.allclose(y_pred_lin, y_check), "Mismatch after reload!"
logger.info("Reload verified: predictions identical to original.")
logger.info(f"Feature order in bundle: {loaded['features']}")
```
